Crash Team Investigation Report
 (For review by the MSP Crash Team)

Narrative:

On may 29th, 2023 at approximately 1239 hours, the Maryland State Police Easton Barrack responded to the intersection of Maryland Route 404 and Maryland Route 16 in Caroline County, Maryland for a report of a motor vehicle collision.  Upon their arrival, they learned that the collision involved a 2001 Honda CR-V and a 2013 Nissan Altima. 

Emergency Medical Services responded to the scene and indicated that one of the parties involved in the collision had sustained life-threatening injuries.  TFC. Mowbray, an Advanced Collision Investigator, responded to the scene. 
TFC. Mowbray photographed and marked the scene for a possible reconstruction.  TFC. Mowbray later contacted me about mapping the scene.  Using a small Unmanned Aerial Vehicle (sUAV) I conducted a flight over the scene obtaining various photographs in a manner which can later be used to create a scaled orthomosaic image similar to what a person would see using Google Earth.  During this flight, I utilized a manual flight path and the camera set to take a photograph every 2 seconds.  By using this method, the sUAV obtained 50 digital photographs.  
 
The images obtained from the sUAV flights were placed into a software called Pix4D.  Pix4d application takes the sUAV’s photographs and identifies common points in the photographs.  The application uses these common points in addition to digital data captured by the sUAV and creates a digital point cloud and an Orthomosaic image.  The Orthomosaic image is a scaled image that has been corrected for lens distortion, perspective, and camera angle. 

A review of the Pix4D quality report for the scene showed no issues that would invalidate the accuracy.  The overall results of the Pix4D was an accurate representation of the scene. 

The Pix4D Orthomosiac image was then imported into the Leica Map360 computer drawing software.  This software allows for various layers to be displayed, measured, and labeled to create final display products.

Investigation Status:

The above report will be provided to TFC. Mowbray for inclusion in his investigation.   Any further investigation will be documented in additional reports.

Detailed Crash Investigation Supplement
(For review by the MSP Crash Team)




Section I. - Narrative
On May 29, 2023, at approximately 1239 hours, Troopers from the Maryland State Police Easton Barrack responded to the area of Maryland Route 404 (Shore Highway) at the intersection of Maryland Route 16 (Greenwood Road), Denton, Caroline County, Maryland to investigate a motor vehicle collision. Upon my arrival at 1253 hours, I found that the collision involved a green 2001 Honda CR-V bearing Maryland registration 4Z7719, a red 2013 Nissan Altima bearing Florida registration CI7517 and a white 2022 Honda CR-V bearing Delaware PC801023. Caroline County Emergency Medical Services responded and determined that the collision involved life-threatening injuries to the rear seat passenger of the Nissan. Due to the nature of the collision and injuries, I conducted an advanced collision investigation.

A preliminary investigation revealed that vehicle one; a green 2001 Honda CR-V, was stopped at the intersection facing southbound on Greenwood Road at Shore Highway. Due to a traffic backup, both eastbound and westbound thru lanes were stopped. Vehicle three; a white 2022 Honda CR-V, was traveling westbound and slowed to stop at the intersection of Greenwood Road due to the traffic backup. Vehicle one proceeded through the flashing red stop light and entered the westbound and then ultimately eastbound lanes of travel. Vehicle two; a red 2013 Nissan Altima, was traveling eastbound on Shore Highway approaching the intersection of Greenwood Road. Vehicle two then entered the right passing lane to legally pass vehicles attempting to turn left onto Greenwood Road. Vehicle one drove southbound and into the path of vehicle two. Vehicle two subsequently struck the front end of vehicle one in a right-angle style collision. As a result of the collision, vehicle two exited the right side of the roadway and struck a guardrail face. Vehicle one subsequently rotated counter-clockwise and struck the front quarter panel of vehicle three.

The driver of the 2001 Honda CR-V; Makayla Nydia Diehl (DOB: 05/28/2001) [hereinafter identified as ‘Diehl’], suffered serious physical injuries as a result of the collision. Caroline County Emergency Medical Services transported Diehl to TidalHealth Nanticoke Memorial Hospital in Seaford, Delaware for treatment of her injuries.

The driver of the 2013 Nissan Altima; Ana Catalina Orjuela Toro (DOB: 05/29/1980) [hereinafter identified as ‘Ana’], and the front seat passenger; Olga Lucia Toro Vargas (DOB: 09/12/1956) [hereinafter identified as ‘Olga’], suffered serious physical injuries as a result of the collision. Caroline County Emergency Medical Services transported both individuals to TidalHealth Peninsula Regional Medical Center in Salisbury, Maryland for treatment of their injuries. The rear seat passenger; Natalia Orjuela Toro (DOB: 09/02/1978) [hereinafter identified as ‘Natalia’], suffered life-threatening injuries as a result of the collision. Due to the weather, the Maryland State Police Aviation Command was unable to make a response. Caroline County Emergency Medical Services transported Natalia to TidalHealth Peninsula Regional Medical Center in Salisbury, Maryland for treatment of her injuries. Natalia was ultimately transferred to the University of Maryland R Adams Cowley Shock Trauma Center in Baltimore, Maryland for treatment after being stabilized in Salisbury.

The driver of the 2022 Honda CR-V; George Edgar Jones (DOB: 02/17/1954) [hereinafter identified as ‘George’], and the passenger; Sara Ann Jones (DOB: 08/05/1959) [hereinafter identified as ‘Sara’], refused medical treatment while at the scene.

While on scene, I made contact with the driver of the white Honda CR-V; George Jones. George was able to provide a written statement on a Maryland State Police form 76. The following is the statement provided by George;
“We were heading west bound on MD 404. Traffic was backed up I stopped at Rt. 16 to let the green car out she pulled out without stopping to see if anyone was coming east bound. She collided with the red car and her car spun into my car.”

While on scene, I made contact with the passenger of the white Honda CR-V; Sara Jones. Sara was able to provide a written statement on a Maryland State Police form 76. The following is the statement provided by Sara;
“There was traffic coming and going. We gave the driver in the green car to our right permission to go on our right. She sped across the road not looking and the red car hit her on right (green car). She spun around and hit our car driver side fender. At this time we don’t know if our silver car is drivable.”

While on scene, I made contact with a separate witness of the collision; identified as Travis Avery Aion (DOB: 06/16/1994) [hereinafter identified as ‘Aion’]. Aion was able to provide a written statement on a Maryland State Police form 76. The following is the statement provided by Aion;
“I was the passenger behind the white CR-V that got scraped. The green CR-V was stopped at the blinking red light on I believe 404. She pulled forward past the white CR-V in front of us, trying to go straight across. There was a blind spot for her because of the long line of cars on 16 west. The red car drove directly into the front right side of the green car. This caused the green car to spin around and lightly knick the white car in front of us. I then got out of the car to check on the woman in the green car. She was in total shock and had a red mark across her face from the airbag. I asked her what her name was & if she knew what year it was. She was slow to answer, but got it right

I proceeded to process the scene by taking digital photographs and marking the roadway evidence.

The green Honda suffered extensive damage starting at the passenger’s side front quarter panel, continuing along the front bumper (see DSCN1249). The green Honda also had red paint transfer, from the collision with the Nissan. I observed the Honda’s front airbags to have been deployed. I also observed the driver’s seatbelt to be loose and locked into position; indicative of the use of the device. The driver’s side of the Honda had minimal damage.

The Nissan was at its final rest against the guardrail on the eastbound portion of the roadway. The Nissan had suffered extensive damage to its front end, more specifically the driver’s side and quarter panel area (see DSCN1224). The Nissan also had damage to the right front quarter panel from the collision with the guardrail face. All four doors were removed for the extrication and rescue of the passengers within the vehicle. I observed the driver’s and front passenger’s seatbelts to be loose and locked into position; indicating they were used during the event of the collision. I observed the right rear passenger’s seatbelt to be locked and retracted against the c-pillar, indicating that it was not in use during the event of the collision. I also observed the front airbags of the Nissan to be deployed.

I also observed gauges to the roadway in the area of impact within the eastbound lane of travel.

The white Honda was parked facing westbound within lane one. The white Honda suffered minimal damage to its driver’s side front quarter panel from the collision with the green Honda (see DSCN. No other remarkable damage was noted to the white Honda.

In the days following the collision, I made contact with personnel from the TidalHealth Peninsula Regional Medical Center. I was advised that Natalia sustained serious physical injuries, but was in and was not stable enough to be transferred to the University of Maryland R Adams Cowley Shock Trauma Center. After several days, Natalia was transferred to the Shock Trauma Center and was ultimately moved to the rehabilitation center following her procedures.

Since the collision, Natalia is at home recovering from her injuries, however still has trouble with her vision.

Conclusion:
The investigation revealed that vehicle one; a green 2001 Honda CR-V, was stopped at the intersection facing southbound on Greenwood Road at Shore Highway. Due to a traffic backup, both eastbound and westbound thru lanes were stopped. Vehicle three; a white 2022 Honda CR-V, was traveling westbound and slowed to stop at the intersection of Greenwood Road due to the traffic backup. Vehicle one proceeded through the flashing red stop light and entered the westbound and then ultimately eastbound lanes of travel. Vehicle two; a red 2013 Nissan Altima, was traveling eastbound on Shore Highway approaching the intersection of Greenwood Road. The Nissan then entered the right passing lane to legally pass vehicles attempting to turn left onto Greenwood Road. The green Honda drove southbound and into the path of the Nissan. The Nissan subsequently struck the front end of the green Honda in a right-angle style collision. As a result of the collision, the Nissan’s redirected to the right where it exited the right side of the roadway and struck a guardrail face. The green Honda subsequently rotated counter-clockwise and struck the front quarter panel of the white Honda.

Since Natalia did not suffer fatal or life-altering injuries it was determined that there was no further need for a detailed investigation. 

The driver of the green Honda; Makayla Diehl was issued the following traffic citation, via certified mail, as a result of the collision;
TA 21-401: FAILURE VEHICLE TO YIELD INTERSECTION RIGHT-OF-WAY TO ANOTHER VEHICLE

I respectfully request that the case be closed by issuance of charging documents.

All events occurred in Caroline County, Maryland.
